We kick off the first of our three [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.20.03.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-6707" title="Liberal Democrat Local, Social, Digital Fringe" src="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.20.03.png" alt="" width="557" height="166" /></a></p>
<blockquote><p>You can sign up to the event <a href="http://localsocialdigitallibdem.eventbrite.com/">here</a> or by visiting <a href="http://www.facebook.com/event.php?eid=260956190593272">our Facebook event page</a>.</p></blockquote>
<p>We kick off the first of our three <a href="http://www.localsocialdigital.com">Local, Social, Digital</a> fringe meetings in Birmingham this Sunday at the <a href="http://www.libdems.org.uk/conference.aspx">Liberal Democrat Conference</a>.  We&#8217;re hoping to get an enthusiastic reception from a party where politicians have already embraced social media. Liberal Democrat MPs were more likely to be than MPs from any other party to be on Facebook, according to this <a href="http://www.hansardsociety.org.uk/files/folders/2090/download.aspx">report from the Hansard Society in 2009</a>, and they also had a higher than average number of friends (although we don&#8217;t know if this has changed recently&#8230;).</p>
<p>Engaging with voters on a personal and local level has always been important to Liberal Democrat campaigners, who have often had to work hard to beat an entrenched, habitual Conservative or Labour vote. This has traditionally been done through the <a href="http://www.electionleaflets.org/parties/liberal_democrats/">Focus newsletter</a>, delivered to local residents doors by Liberal Democrat activists. However, now the party is in coalition government, activists and politicians are having to think differently about how they communicate to win the trust and support of local voters.</p>
<p>Local, Social, Digital is not just about winning elections though, it is also about the delivery of public services. Now the Liberal Democrats do hold seats in the Government and continue to run local councils up and down the country, politicians have the opportunity to influence how this is done. They can bring their values to life by enabling services to be designing with user involvement and testing at every stage. They can create new structures of decision making that really devolve power. At this fringe meeting we will be hearing from our panellists and audience members about how this can be achieved, we will be challenging each other&#8217;s thinking and coming away with new ideas to change the way we do things.</p>
<p><strong>Speakers:</strong></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.julianhuppert.org.uk/">Dr Julian Huppert MP</a> </strong>was elected in 2010 as the member of parliament for Cambridge and was <a href="http://www.libdemvoice.org/ldv-survey-the-new-lib-dem-mps-whove-impressed-party-members-the-most-22730.html">voted the most impressive new MP by Liberal Democrat members</a>. Julian is a regular user of both Facebook and <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/julianhuppert">Twitter</a>.  He has campaigned against the Digital Economy Bill, both <a href="http://www.libdemvoice.org/digital-economy-bill-latest-two-cheers-for-the-libdem-team-18552.html">before</a> he was elected and <a href="http://www.libdemvoice.org/julian-huppert-mp-calls-for-digital-economy-act-rethink-24471.html">after</a>. Julian is a member of the Home Affairs Select Committee and made use of social media to communicate with people about his questioning of the former Metropolitan Police Commissioner, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Stephenson_(police_officer)">Sir Paul Stephenson</a>, and others involved with policing the phone hacking scandal.</p>
<p><a href="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.09.49.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-6703" title="Julian Huppert MP's Facebook Page" src="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.09.49.png" alt="" width="522" height="473" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.markpack.org.uk/"><strong>Dr Mark Pack</strong> </a>is the Head of Digital at <a href="http://www.mhpc.com/">MHP Communications</a> and Co-Editor of <a href="http://www.libdemvoice.org/">Liberal Democrat Voice</a>, the most widely-read Liberal Democrat blog in the UK. Previously he was Head of Innovations at the Liberal Democrats, where he ran the party&#8217;s 2001 and 2005 internet general election campaigns. Mark is also a member of the <a href="http://www.openrightsgroup.org/">Open Rights Group</a>&#8217;s Advisory Council.</p>
<p>Mark spoke to us in advance of the fringe meeting and said: &#8220;Digital technology can provide an important route for councils to better serve their residents and politicians to better serve their electors. However, there is a yawning gap between what is current being done and what is already known to be best practice in many parts of the country, let alone between the current situation and the opportunities the future will open up.&#8221;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.17.46.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-6705" title="Mark Pack on Liberal Democrat Voice" src="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.17.46.png" alt="" width="574" height="235" /></a></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://twitter.com/#!/CllrDaisyBenson">Cllr Daisy Benson</a> </strong>is a councillor, and leader of the Liberal Democrat opposition group, on <a href="http://www.reading.gov.uk/">Reading Borough Council</a>. Daisy is an avid blogger and tweeter, and has regularly posts on her blog, <a href="http://daisyscampaigndiary.blogspot.com/">Daisy&#8217;s Campaign Diary</a>, and her ward website, <a href="http://www.redlandslibdems.org.uk/">Redlands Liberal Democrats</a>.</p>
<p>Daisy understands the concerns of other councillors who are apprehensive about using online tools, but is keen to share her positive experiences with others. She said: &#8221;Social media cannot replace traditional forms of communication, but it does help to bring elected representatives closer to their electorate I think. I use Twitter and my blog to give people a better idea what I do and also as a way of keeping my ear to the ground in the community I represent.&#8221;</p>
<p><a href="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.15.55.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-6704" title="Daisy's Campaign Dairy" src="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.15.55.png" alt="" width="561" height="387" /></a></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://twitter.com/#!/EmmaMaier">Emma Maier</a></strong> is the editor of the <a href="http://www.lgcplus.com/">Local Government Chronicle</a> and will be chairing the meeting. Emma has a specialist interest in online journalism and regularly communicates with members of the local government community via Twitter.</p>
<p><a href="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.18.41.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-6706" title="Emma Maier's Twitter account" src="http://wearefuturegov.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Screen-shot-2011-09-14-at-13.18.41.png" alt="" width="542" height="444" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Event:</strong></p>
<p>Room 116, <a href="http://birminghamhotels.jurysinns.com/">Jurys Inn</a>, 245 Broad Street, Birmingham, B1 2HQ (conference passes not needed)<br />
Date: Sunday 18th September 2011<br />
Time: 1 &#8211; 2pm</p>
<p>Refreshments (wine, fruit sticks and muffins) will be served.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Futuregov/~4/K4oksPLgb2Q" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
